# Phase 1: Common Package Foundation Walkthrough

The restructuring of the shared foundation layer is fully complete. The project now benefits from a clean, centralized, and extensible package structure for all core capabilities.

## Architecture & Structure Update

The `com.zencube.registry.common` package has been reorganized as follows:

```text
common/
├── audit
│   ├── AuditorAwareImpl.java
│   └── AuditorConfig.java
├── constants
│   └── Constants.java
├── entity
│   └── BaseEntity.java
├── enums
│   ├── ApplicationStatus.java
│   └── ... (existing enums)
├── exception
│   ├── BadRequestException.java
│   ├── BaseException.java
│   ├── ConflictException.java
│   ├── GlobalExceptionHandler.java
│   └── ... (other custom exceptions)
├── mapper          (placeholder for mapstruct / mappers)
├── response
│   ├── ApiResponse.java
│   └── ErrorResponse.java
├── util            (placeholder for core utilities)
└── validation      (placeholder for core validators)
```

## Highlights

1. **Centralized Error Handling**: 
   Moved the robust `GlobalExceptionHandler` and all application exceptions (e.g., `ResourceNotFoundException`, `ForbiddenException`) to `common/exception` and removed duplicate legacy code.
   
2. **Audit Configuration**: 
   Grouped Spring JPA Audit features (`AuditorAwareImpl`, `AuditorConfig`) into `common/audit` taking them out from the security domain to properly enforce separation of concerns.
   
3. **API Contracts**: 
   Isolated `ApiResponse` and `ErrorResponse` inside `common/response` to clearly define our outward-facing DTO contracts.

4. **Widespread Global Imports Updated**: 
   Updated over 40+ controllers, entities, and services that had dependencies on these files.
   
## Verification

I executed a `mvn clean compile` across the updated project space. The codebase compiled successfully with a `BUILD SUCCESS`, confirming all class movements, package namespaces, and import resolutions are intact and fully functional.

> [!TIP]
> The foundation is now strictly organized. When adding future modules (e.g., candidate management, projects, education), please refer to these centralized base structures to ensure enterprise-grade consistency.
